stylometry: The tradeoff managers must consider when dealing with waiting lines is balancing the service cost (number of channels X cost per channel) and and the waiting cost (cost per time per unit X the average units). In general terms, it is the cost of paying for servers/channels vs. the cost of lost business because of wait time. The objective is to minimize the wait time and also the service cost based upon the service level chosen by the organization. We hope to maximize server/channel utilization. Variables that affect these choices include the arrival rate of customers (Poisson-at lot a first and then less and less, or random), service facility layout (number of channels, servers), and line characteristics (length, type such as FIFO or others). Other numbers such as the number of customers total, probabilities of particular amounts of customers, the probability of the service facility being idle, average time in line, and the average length of the line must also be considering when making a final decision. Overall we are looking at time and cost minimization, with profit maximization.
